  # Cross-category scientific analysis
  {"id":"fqa-cross-009","category":"swords","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does metallographic analysis distinguish tamahagane from modern steel in Japanese swords?","answer":"Metallographic analysis of polished and etched cross-sections reveals the steel's internal structure. Tamahagane (traditional smelted steel) shows: heterogeneous carbon distribution (0.1-1.3% C) creating visible layers from the folding process; slag inclusions (non-metallic particles) elongated along the forging direction — these are inevitable in traditional smelting and serve as authenticity markers; ferrite-pearlite banding from differential carbon zones created during folding; and phosphorus-rich zones visible as bright areas in Nital-etched sections. Modern steel, by contrast, shows: uniform carbon distribution; absence of or minimal slag inclusions; uniform grain structure without folding artifacts; and controlled alloy elements (chromium, vanadium) not present in traditional Japanese steel. The number of visible folding layers provides evidence of the forging process — typically 10-15 folds (creating 1024-32768 layers). Excessive folding beyond 15-16 times actually degrades the steel by over-refining the grain. This metallographic evidence is considered one of the most reliable authentication methods, though it requires a microscopic sample.","evidence":["Yaso Kazu, Metallurgy of Japanese Swords","NBTHK scientific analysis reports"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["metallography","tamahagane","steel-analysis","cross-section"]},
  {"id":"fqa-cross-010","category":"ceramics","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does neutron activation analysis (NAA) help trace Japanese ceramic provenance to specific kilns?","answer":"NAA determines trace element composition with extremely high sensitivity, creating a 'chemical fingerprint' of the clay body. Each kiln site uses clay from specific geological deposits with unique trace element profiles. The technique irradiates a small sample with neutrons, creating radioactive isotopes whose gamma emissions identify and quantify elements at parts-per-million levels. For Japanese ceramics, NAA databases exist for major kiln complexes: Mino (Oribe, Shino), Seto, Karatsu, Arita, Bizen, Hagi, and others. Key discriminating elements include rare earth elements (La, Ce, Sm, Eu), transition metals (Cr, Co, Sc), and alkali metals (Rb, Cs). NAA can distinguish between neighboring kiln sites that use different clay deposits, and can identify pieces made from mixed clays. Limitations include the requirement for a small sample (50-100mg, typically from the unglazed foot), and the need for comprehensive reference databases. Despite these limitations, NAA has resolved numerous attribution disputes — notably confirming that certain 'Ko-Kutani' pieces were actually produced at Arita kilns in Kyushu.","evidence":["Neff, Neutron Activation Analysis of Japanese Ceramics","Smithsonian Archaeometry laboratory"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["NAA","provenance","kiln-attribution","trace-elements"]},
  {"id":"fqa-cross-011","category":"ukiyoe","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does Raman spectroscopy identify pigments in Japanese woodblock prints?","answer":"Raman spectroscopy identifies molecular structure through inelastic light scattering, making it ideal for non-destructive pigment identification on ukiyo-e prints. Key applications: Prussian blue (bero-ai) — introduced to Japan around 1829, shows characteristic Raman peaks at 2154 cm⁻¹ (CN stretch). Its presence sets a terminus post quem for prints claiming earlier dates. Indigo (ai) — natural plant-derived blue used before Prussian blue introduction, shows peaks at 1572, 1364, 252 cm⁻¹. Vermillion (shu) — mercury sulfide shows intense peak at 252 cm⁻¹. Distinguishable from modern cadmium reds. Red lead (entan) — Pb₃O₄ shows peaks at 549, 121 cm⁻¹, used in early prints. Chrome yellow — CrO₄ peaks appear only in post-1809 prints. Organic colorants like safflower red (beni) and turmeric yellow (ukon) have weaker Raman signatures but are identifiable with enhanced techniques (SERS). Raman is completely non-destructive, requires no sample preparation, and can be performed through protective glazing. It is increasingly the first-line scientific analysis for print authentication.","evidence":["Burgio & Clark, Raman spectroscopy of pigments","National Museum of Japanese History pigment studies"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["raman","pigments","spectroscopy","non-destructive"]},
  # Market intelligence QAs
  {"id":"fqa-market-001","category":"swords","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"What factors create the largest price differentials in the Japanese sword market?","answer":"The Japanese sword market shows extreme price variation based on several interacting factors: NBTHK certification level — the single largest value driver. A blade jumping from Hozon to Juyo can increase 5-10x in value. Tokubetsu Juyo pieces are in a rarefied tier. Smith attribution — named smiths command premiums over school attributions. Within named smiths, hierarchy follows historical reputation: Masamune, Sadamune, Go Yoshihiro at the apex. Period — Koto (pre-1596) generally commands higher prices than Shinto or Shinshinto of equivalent quality, though exceptional later works can exceed average Koto prices. Condition — original condition (ubu) nakago vs. shortened (suriage) significantly impacts value. Recent quality polish vs. tired old polish also matters. Provenance — daimyo collection history, publication in sword references, and exhibition history all add premium. The interaction between these factors creates the 100x+ spread seen in the market: an unsigned, uncertified Shinshinto blade might sell for $2,000, while a signed, NBTHK Juyo Koto blade by a famous smith with daimyo provenance could reach $500,000+.","evidence":["Recent Bonhams/Christie's Japanese sword results","NBTHK valuation guidelines"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["market","pricing","valuation-factors","swords"]},
  {"id":"fqa-market-002","category":"ceramics","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"Why do certain tea ceremony wares command disproportionate prices relative to comparable ceramics?","answer":"Tea ceremony context creates a unique value framework that transcends conventional art market pricing. A simple Raku tea bowl may sell for 10-100x the price of a technically superior but non-tea-associated piece. Key factors: Provenance chain through tea masters — documented use by a recognized iemoto (head of a tea school) can multiply value by orders of magnitude. The tea ceremony treats selected objects as having 'personality' and 'story.' Meibutsu designation — pieces listed in classical tea catalogues (Meibutsu-ki) by Matsudaira Fumai or Kobori Enshu have established canonical status, creating a ceiling-less price category. Wabi aesthetic premium — the tea tradition values imperfection, asymmetry, and natural accident (景色 keshiki). Features that would be defects in other ceramics — crawling glaze, kiln marks, repairs — become desirable. Box (hakogaki) inscription — calligraphy by a tea master naming the piece adds significant value, sometimes exceeding the ceramic's intrinsic worth. Cultural scarcity — genuine tea-associated pieces from Momoyama/early Edo are finite. As global collector interest grows, supply-demand dynamics create upward pressure.","evidence":["Christies Tea Ceremony Arts results","Hayashiya, Japanese Art of Tea"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["tea-ceremony","market","valuation","meibutsu"]},
  {"id":"fqa-market-003","category":"contemporary","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How has the globalization of the contemporary art market affected Japanese art authentication?","answer":"Globalization has transformed Japanese contemporary art authentication in several ways: Increased forgery incentive — Kusama, Nara, and Murakami prices have risen 10-50x in the past 15 years, making forgery increasingly profitable. Online marketplace proliferation has created new channels for unverified works. Foundation response — artist foundations have professionalized authentication processes, with Yayoi Kusama Studio, Kaikai Kiki, and others maintaining comprehensive databases and issuing formal certificates. Cross-border jurisdiction — works may be offered in jurisdictions with weaker consumer protection, complicating legal recourse for buyers of forgeries. The Japan Art Dealers Association has limited enforcement power outside Japan. Digital authentication tools — some contemporary artists now incorporate hidden authentication markers (UV-reactive elements, embedded RFID, blockchain registration). Murakami has explored NFT-linked authentication. Market education — major auction houses now require foundation certificates for high-value Japanese contemporary lots, effectively making foundation authentication a market standard. However, secondary market sales (galleries, private treaty, online) still frequently lack this verification.","evidence":["Art Basel/UBS Art Market Report","Japan Art Dealers Association guidelines"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["globalization","market","authentication-trends","contemporary"]},
  # Additional specialized QAs
  {"id":"fqa-cross-012","category":"lacquerware","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does radiocarbon dating apply to Japanese lacquerware authentication?","answer":"Radiocarbon (C-14) dating can determine the age of organic materials in lacquerware: the wooden substrate, the urushi lacquer itself, and any organic decorative materials. For lacquerware, the technique is particularly powerful because: urushi is an organic material that can be directly dated — the lacquer's C-14 content reflects when the sap was harvested, providing a maximum age for the application; wooden substrate dating establishes the age of the carved form independently of the lacquer surface; and in cases of re-lacquering (common in restorations), C-14 can distinguish between original and later lacquer layers. Limitations include: sample size requirements (minimum 10-50mg of organic material); the wood 'old wood effect' — timber from ancient trees gives dates older than the carving; and the need for careful sample selection to avoid contamination. AMS (Accelerator Mass Spectrometry) C-14 dating requires smaller samples and can be performed on individual lacquer layers. The technique has been used to authenticate several important lacquerware pieces where stylistic dating was disputed, notably resolving controversies about Kamakura-period lacquer boxes.","evidence":["National Museum of Japanese History C-14 dating program","Kudo et al., AMS dating of urushi lacquer"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["radiocarbon","C-14","lacquer-dating","scientific-analysis"]},
  {"id":"fqa-cross-013","category":"textiles","difficulty":"expert","question":"How do mordant analysis and dye identification authenticate Japanese textile traditions?","answer":"Mordant and dye analysis provides both material identification and geographic/temporal provenance. Traditional Japanese dyeing uses specific mordant-dye combinations: aluminum mordants (from alum — myoban) with plant dyes create characteristic color fastness patterns. Iron mordants (from ferrous acetate — haguro) produce the distinctive dark purplish-black of Japanese iron-mordanted dyes. Tin mordants brighten colors but were used later in the tradition. Analytical methods include: HPLC (High Performance Liquid Chromatography) separating dye molecules by molecular weight — distinguishing natural indigo (indigotin + indirubin) from synthetic (indigotin only); mass spectrometry identifying specific plant-derived compounds unique to Japanese dye sources (e.g., specific flavonoids from Japanese murasaki root for purple); and SEM-EDS identifying mordant metal particles embedded in fibers. Period indicators: pre-Meiji textiles use exclusively natural dyes; early Meiji (1868-1890) shows a transition period with both natural and early synthetic dyes; and post-1890 synthetic dyes become increasingly dominant. The detection of synthetic dyes in a textile claiming pre-Meiji origin is definitive evidence of later date or modern production.","evidence":["Kyoto Institute of Technology dye chemistry lab","Sasaki, Natural Dyes of Japan"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["mordant","dye-analysis","HPLC","textile-chemistry"]},
  {"id":"fqa-cross-014","category":"swords","difficulty":"expert","question":"What role does dendrochronology play in authenticating Japanese sword mountings (koshirae)?","answer":"Dendrochronology — dating wood by matching annual growth ring patterns to established regional chronologies — authenticates sword mountings by dating the wooden components: scabbard (saya), handle core (tsuka), and storage chest (katana-dansu). Japanese dendrochronology benefits from well-established chronologies for hinoki (Japanese cypress), sugi (Japanese cedar), and other native species extending back thousands of years. For koshirae authentication: saya wood dating provides a terminus post quem for the mounting — the wood cannot have been worked before the tree was felled; handle core wood dates verify consistency with claimed mounting period; and storage chest dating can establish collection history. Critical limitations: wood may be significantly older than the mounting if recycled timber was used; some scabbards use tropical hardwoods (magnolia — honoki) whose growth rings are less reliable for dating due to inconsistent growing seasons; and the outer lacquer layers prevent non-destructive access to the wood surface. CT scanning can sometimes reveal ring patterns through lacquer without sampling. When dendrochronology confirms a mounting's period consistency with its blade, the combined evidence substantially strengthens attribution.","evidence":["Nara National Research Institute for Cultural Properties dendrochronology lab","Mitsutani, Japanese Dendrochronology Database"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["dendrochronology","koshirae","wood-dating","scientific-authentication"]},
  {"id":"fqa-cross-015","category":"ceramics","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How does petrographic analysis reveal ceramic production origin?","answer":"Petrographic analysis examines thin sections (30 microns) of ceramic bodies under polarized light microscopy, identifying mineral inclusions that link a piece to specific geological formations and kiln sites. For Japanese ceramics: each kiln region uses clay from distinct geological formations containing characteristic mineral assemblages — Bizen clay is rich in iron-bearing minerals; Seto clay contains specific feldspar varieties; Arita porcelain stone (touseki) has a distinctive quartz and sericite composition. The technique identifies: temper type and grain size — intentionally added materials (sand, crushed pottery, rice chaff) that vary by tradition; natural inclusion assemblage — minerals inherent in the clay that fingerprint the geological source; firing temperature indicators — specific mineral transformations occur at known temperatures, confirming or contradicting claimed firing methods; and manufacturing technique evidence — clay mixing, coil building, wheel throwing each produce distinct micro-structural features. Petrographic analysis requires only a small sample from the unglazed foot and provides complementary evidence to chemical analysis methods like XRF and NAA.","evidence":["Rice, Pottery Analysis: A Sourcebook","Kyoto University archaeological ceramics lab"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["petrography","ceramic-analysis","thin-section","kiln-attribution"]},
  {"id":"fqa-market-004","category":"bonsai","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"What unique factors drive pricing in the international bonsai market?","answer":"The bonsai market operates differently from traditional art markets due to the living nature of the medium. Unique pricing factors include: Living asset risk — unlike static art, bonsai can die from disease, neglect, or environmental stress, creating inherent depreciation risk that must be priced into valuation. This paradoxically makes well-maintained ancient specimens more valuable as survivors. Species hierarchy — Japanese black pine (Kuromatsu) and Japanese white pine (Goyomatsu) command the highest prices. Juniper (Shinpaku) follows closely. Deciduous species generally command lower prices except for exceptional specimens. Exhibition pedigree — Kokufu-ten prize winners represent the pinnacle. Other major exhibitions (Taikan-ten, Sakufu-ten) add value but less dramatically. Non-exhibited trees are valued primarily on intrinsic qualities. Pot-tree pairing — the container is integral to valuation. An antique Chinese kowatari pot can represent 30-50% of a bonsai composition's total value. Seasonal timing — bonsai are typically sold during winter dormancy when transportation risk is lowest, creating seasonal market patterns. Export regulations — USDA phytosanitary requirements for importing bonsai to the US (bare-root, soil removal) add cost and risk, creating price premiums for domestically available specimens in Western markets.","evidence":["Bonsai Focus market analysis articles","International bonsai auction results"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["bonsai-market","pricing","valuation","export"]},
  {"id":"fqa-cross-016","category":"sculpture","difficulty":"expert","question":"How does 3D scanning technology aid in Buddhist sculpture authentication and conservation?","answer":"3D scanning has revolutionized Buddhist sculpture analysis through several applications: Surface geometry documentation — sub-millimeter accurate 3D models preserve the exact surface condition at the time of scanning, enabling detection of future changes (deterioration, restoration interventions). Tool mark analysis — 3D surface mapping reveals carving tool marks invisible to the naked eye, enabling comparison of tool types, cutting angles, and carving sequences across multiple works attributed to the same carver or workshop. Comparative morphometry — precise measurement of proportional systems (face-to-body ratio, hand-to-arm proportion) identifies workshop-specific canons that serve as attribution evidence. Kei school sculptures, for example, follow proportional systems documented in medieval texts. Internal structure visualization — photogrammetric scanning of the interior cavity (when accessible through maintenance hatches) reveals construction methods without X-ray. Virtual reassembly — for damaged or disassembled sculptures, 3D scanning enables digital reassembly to verify that components belong together. Forgery detection — 3D comparison between a questioned piece and authenticated museum examples can reveal whether the piece is a direct copy (showing identical proportions from a mold or digital template) versus an independent creation.","evidence":["Nara National Museum 3D documentation project","Tokyo National Research Institute digital heritage studies"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["3D-scanning","digital-documentation","conservation","authentication"]},
  {"id":"fqa-cross-017","category":"metalwork","difficulty":"intermediate","question":"How does the Japanese concept of 'patina' (sabi/fūgō) differ across material categories?","answer":"Japanese aesthetic tradition values patina — the surface changes that occur through aging and use — as a positive quality rather than deterioration. This concept manifests differently across materials: Iron (tetsu) — tsuba and other iron fittings develop iron oxide patina ranging from reddish-brown to deep black. Each stage has aesthetic terminology: akasabi (red rust, undesirable), kurosabi (black patina, desirable), and the ultimate tetsusabi (iron patina, deep black with blue-violet undertones). Copper alloys — shakudo develops a deep blue-black through rokusho patination; shibuichi develops gray-silver tones. Each alloy's patina is deliberately cultivated and aesthetically valued. Bronze — temple bells and Buddhist implements develop verdigris (rokusho-sabi) that is traditionally preserved. Lacquer — aged urushi develops depth and warmth, with the lacquer becoming more translucent over centuries, allowing the underlying ground to subtly influence the surface color. Wood — exposure creates silvery-gray weathering (fūkasabi) valued in architectural and bonsai contexts. Understanding these patina aesthetics is crucial for authentication because inappropriate cleaning or re-patination destroys historical evidence and reduces value significantly.","evidence":["Ogawa, Japanese Metalwork Techniques","Kyoto craft conservation literature"],"related_assets":[],"tags":["patina","sabi","aesthetics","cross-material"]},
